,"5-beta reductase","5-alpha reductase","17-alpha hydroxylase"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe enzyme \u003Cstrong\u003E5-alpha reductase\u003C/strong\u003E converts testosterone to dihydrotestosterone (DHT) in target tissues. DHT is more potent than testosterone and is crucial for male external genitalia development and male secondary sexual characteristics.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E3-beta hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003E17-beta hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase\u003C/strong\u003E are involved in earlier steps of steroid hormone synthesis. \u003Cstrong\u003E5-beta reductase\u003C/strong\u003E produces different metabolites that are less active. \u003Cstrong\u003E17-alpha hydroxylase\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in cortisol and androgen synthesis pathways but not in DHT formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Testosterone is converted to dihydrotestosterone by the enzyme 5-alpha reductase","Dihydrotestosterone is more potent than testosterone and is essential for male sexual development"],"references":["Al-Zoubi RM, Yassin AA, Alwani M, Al-Qudimat A, Aboumarzouk OM, Zarour A, Al Ansari A. A systematic review on the latest developments in testosterone therapy: Innovations, advances, and paradigm shifts. Arab J Urol. 2021 Aug 8;19(3):370-375. doi: 10.1080/2090598X.2021.1959260. PMID: 34552788; PMCID: PMC8451690.","Nassar GN, Leslie SW. Physiology, Testosterone. [Updated 2023 Jan 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526128/","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media.","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision